 We still have many hands here. 

61
00:03:53,833 --> 00:03:56,200
Now, keep your hands up

62
00:03:56,200 --> 00:03:58,766
If you're already started using StoreKit 2.

63
00:04:00,233 --> 00:04:01,533
Wow

64
00:04:01,533 --> 00:04:03,466
 It's more than my imagination.

65
00:04:03,466 --> 00:04:04,133
Okay

66
00:04:04,133 --> 00:04:05,300
 Thank you very much.

67
00:04:05,300 --> 00:04:06,766
 You can all put your hands down.

68
00:04:08,766 --> 00:04:10,666
 what I've seen

69
00:04:10,666 --> 00:04:15,366
We don't have all people here starting using StoreKit 2 yet

70
00:04:15,366 --> 00:04:20,000
 which is great. It means this  talk is still useful for many  of you. 

71
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:20,700
Now

72
00:04:20,700 --> 00:04:24,133
let's start to see how StoreKit has evolved. 

73
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:27,900
Actually, there’s no “official StoreKit 1.”

74
00:04:27,900 --> 00:04:30,766
Its real name is...

75
00:04:30,766 --> 00:04:33,766
Original API for In-App Purchase

76
00:04:33,766 --> 00:04:35,766
but that’s a bit too long

77
00:04:35,933 --> 00:04:38,500
So I’ll just call it StoreKit 1.

78
00:04:39,766 --> 00:04:42,766
StoreKit 1 was introduced in 2009

79
00:04:42,766 --> 00:04:44,766
 It is delegate based

80
00:04:44,766 --> 00:04:49,333
and requires manual management of the payment queue.

81
00:04:49,333 --> 00:04:52,100
 If you want to make a purchase

82
00:04:52,100 --> 00:04:56,533
You have to make a payment with the product

83
00:04:57,100 --> 00:05:00,566
And add the payment to the paymentQueue.

84
00:05:00,666 --> 00:05:03,766
And there’s even more after that.

85
00:05:04,766 --> 00:05:08,033
Don’t worry you don’t have to learn this

86
00:05:08,033 --> 00:05:11,566
and hopefully you’ll never need to in your whole life

87
00:05:11,566 --> 00:05:18,766
All I want to show is: StoreKit 1 is wordy and fragile.

88
00:05:20,466 --> 00:05:23,966
StoreKit 2 came out in 2021

89
00:05:23,966 --> 00:05:29,400
built on Swift Concurrency, making everything straightforward

90
00:05:29,400 --> 00:05:31,700
If you want to make a purchase

91
00:05:31,700 --> 00:05:35,400
just call product.purchase()

92
00:05:35,400 --> 00:05:36,666
 That's it

93
00:05:36,666 --> 00:05:39,633
One single line, you get a result.

94
00:05:39,633 --> 00:05:42,333
it’s fully scoped and type safe.

95
00:05:42,866 --> 00:05:44,100
Sweet!

96
00:05:45,433 --> 00:05:46,766
 For receipt

97
00:05:46,766 --> 00:05:52,366
StoreKit 1 gives you a unified receipt that
containing all purchases in the app,

98
00:05:52,533 --> 00:05:56,200
you have to parse and validate yourself

99
00:05:57,600 --> 00:06:01,300
StoreKit 2 provides Transaction objects

100
00:06:01,300 --> 00:06:09,566
which contain productID, purchaseDate, and many other information.

101
00:06:09,566 --> 00:06:16,766
Unlike StoreKit 1, StoreKit 2 allows you to directly access one transaction at a time.

102
00:06:16,766 --> 00:06:24,366
It is much more easier to retrieve detailed information and customize your purchase flow

103
00:06:25,200 --> 00:06:32,300
I used two examples to show how StoreKit2 provides easier and modern way to handle purchases.

104
00:06:32,300 --> 00:06:37,966
Now, let’s move on to KKBOX implementation context.

105
00:06:38,766 --> 00:06:41,033
 For music streaming,

106
00:06:41,733 --> 00:06:46,766
we use StoreKit 1 with the verifyReceipt API.

107
00:06:46,766 --> 00:06:49,666
Both subscriptions types are supported

108
00:06:49,666 --> 00:06:52,766
We didn’t have consumable product.

109
00:06:54,266 --> 00:07:00,433
It works with our legacy billing system which only handles music transactions.

110
00:07:01,233 --> 00:07:07,100
The system works reliably in production for many many years.

111
00:07:09,233 --> 00:07:10,533
FanKlub

112
00:07:10,533 --> 00:07:15,900
our new business model, works differently from music streaming

113
00:07:16,666 --> 00:07:21,900
it uses consumable, built with Swift Concurrency.

114
00:07:22,600 --> 00:07:28,133
And we have a new billing system that only handles FanKlub transactions.

115
00:07:28,566 --> 00:07:33,066
With so many differences in logic and architecture

116
00:07:33,066 --> 00:07:38,033
we needed to find an approach that cost the least development effort

117
00:07:38,033 --> 00:07:42,500
To figure that out, we explored three options.

118
00:07:44,233 --> 00:07:45,766
Option 1

119
00:07:45,766 --> 00:07:48,066
Fully move to StoreKit 2.

120
00:07:48,300 --> 00:07:50,766
But this is risky

121
00:07:50,766 --> 00:07:56,766
Because it changes important parts of our app that have been stable for years

122
00:07:57,466 --> 00:08:05,566
 And you would need to have very close teamwork, with the billing and App team

123
00:08:06,333 --> 00:08:12,400
 The timeline is hard to predict, and it could delay the FanKlub launch

124
00:08:12,400 --> 00:08:15,233
So option 2,

125
00:08:15,233 --> 00:08:17,566
 stay with StoreKit 1.

126
00:08:17,566 --> 00:08:22,466
It sounds safer, but it actually has a big problem.

127
00:08:23,066 --> 00:08:28,766
StoreKit 1 and the verifyReceipt API are already deprecated

128
00:08:30,066 --> 00:08:31,433
 Option 3

129
00:08:31,433 --> 00:08:32,766
Hybrid approach! 

130
00:08:32,766 --> 00:08:35,800
and that’s the one we chose.

131
00:08:35,800 --> 00:08:42,233
We use StoreKit 1 for music streaming and StoreKit 2 for FanKlub.

132
00:08:42,233 --> 00:08:50,700
Apple allows mixing both API if we support iOS 15 or later, which we do.

133
00:08:50,766 --> 00:08:55,033
This way, we can keep our stable legacy flow,

134
00:08:55,033 --> 00:08:58,766
adopt StoreKit 2 for our new features

135
00:08:58,766 --> 00:09:02,333
take advantage of Swift Concurrency

136
00:09:02,333 --> 00:09:07,466
and reduce risk while preparing for a future migration.

137
00:09:09,200 --> 00:09:10,766
 To recap

138
00:09:11,666 --> 00:09:19,600
StoreKit 2 provide a modern and easier way compared to StoreKit 1 to handle purchase

139
00:09:20,100 --> 00:09:26,033
To balance stability and innovation, we chose a hybrid approach.

140
00:09:26,333 --> 00:09:35,166
The trade-off is that now we have to maintain two flows, which means more complexity

141
00:09:35,300 --> 00:09:38,833
 Next, I’ll walk you through how we handle that.

142
00:09:40,433 --> 00:09:46,400
Let’s start with a quick overview of how StoreKit handles transaction history

143
00:09:46,766 --> 00:09:51,566
All transactions—whether using StoreKit 1 or StoreKit 2

144
00:09:51,566 --> 00:09:54,533
are visible across both APIs

145
00:09:54,533 --> 00:10:01,433
which means purchases made with StoreKit 1 can be accessed through StoreKit 2

146
00:10:01,433 --> 00:10:08,133
and StoreKit 2 purchases also appear in the unified receipt used by StoreKit 1

147
00:10:08,133 --> 00:10:14,300
This cross-visibility is intentional and documented by Apple

148
00:10:14,500 --> 00:10:23,766
But when both APIs used in the same app, it requires careful handling to avoid duplicate processing.

149
00:10:24,600 --> 00:10:27,366
So here comes the first problem.

150
00:10:28,500 --> 00:10:35,766
StoreKit 1 receives updates from StoreKit 2 purchases—and vice versa

151
00:10:35,766 --> 00:10:41,966
There’s no built in separation, which could easily lead to double-processing.

152
00:10:42,600 --> 00:10:48,000
To fix this, we use productID to filter logic

153
00:10:48,366 --> 00:10:52,566
 All FanKlub productIDs contain fanKlub

154
00:10:52,700 --> 00:10:54,766
In StoreKit 1

155
00:10:55,833 --> 00:10:58,700
we skip fanKlub products

156
00:10:58,700 --> 00:11:04,200
In StoreKit 2, we only handle fanKlub products.

157
00:11:04,400 --> 00:11:08,433
 filtering gives us a clear separation.

158
00:11:09,966 --> 00:11:11,500
 Problem 2.

159
00:11:11,500 --> 00:11:14,000
Mixed Receipt Validation

160
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:20,333
StoreKit 1 gives you a unified receipt that contains all purchases in the app

161
00:11:20,400 --> 00:11:27,366
 So it contains music streaming and  FanKlub transactions

162
00:11:27,366 --> 00:11:32,866
which our legacy billing system wasn't designed to handle that

163
00:11:33,166 --> 00:11:34,766
 To fix this,

164
00:11:35,900 --> 00:11:43,966
we update our backend to ignore any transactions  related to FanKlub.

165
00:11:43,966 --> 00:11:48,766
This way, the receipt upload won't break legacy logic.

166
00:11:49,700 --> 00:11:54,366
Above challenges are the traits documented by Apple.

167
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:59,200
But there’s no document that covers all scenarios.

168
00:12:00,100 --> 00:12:06,400
The tools provided by Apple really helped us a lot.

169
00:12:06,400 --> 00:12:12,766
They affect In-App Purchase behavior whether we use StoreKit 1 or StoreKit 2

170
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:20,166
In the early development stage, we use StoreKit Testing in Xcode.

171
00:12:20,433 --> 00:12:24,866
It doesn’t require internet or App Store Connect.

172
00:12:24,866 --> 00:12:27,633
It’s like an offline playground

173
00:12:28,400 --> 00:12:32,666
The testing configuration file provides many different options

174
00:12:32,666 --> 00:12:37,433
that can remind you to handle scenarios that may happen.

175
00:12:37,433 --> 00:12:38,766
 In our case,

176
00:12:38,766 --> 00:12:44,766
 it reminded us to handle the “Ask to Buy” flow, which we hadn’t planned for

177
00:12:46,400 --> 00:12:49,533
Once the flow is planned and built,

178
00:12:49,533 --> 00:12:56,133
We use App Store sandbox with App Store Connect productID to test the flow

179
00:12:56,900 --> 00:12:58,233
 In this stage

180
00:12:58,233 --> 00:13:02,833
we test both the legacy flow and the new FanKlub flow 

181
00:13:02,833 --> 00:13:04,400
 including

182
00:13:04,766 --> 00:13:09,066
 sending sandbox receipts to our server.

183
00:13:09,233 --> 00:13:15,500
Most of the issues with the app server are discovered and solved in this stage

184
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:17,000
 In our case,

185
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:21,766
we found a FanKlub transaction inside the unified receipt

186
00:13:21,766 --> 00:13:27,566
and when it was sent to our backend, it caused backend errors

187
00:13:27,900 --> 00:13:28,766
 Finally

188
00:13:28,766 --> 00:13:33,733
we uploaded to TestFlight for internal testers to test the flow.

189
00:13:33,733 --> 00:13:39,333
Because all transactions are in a sandbox environment for TestFlight reviewers

190
00:13:39,333 --> 00:13:43,700
so people can test whatever they want without being charged

191
00:13:44,200 --> 00:13:48,233
It helped us improve the user experience

192
00:13:48,233 --> 00:13:53,900
Once everything was set up, we submitted our product to app review.

193
00:13:54,100 --> 00:14:01,433
Normally, the review process is straightforward and doesn’t require any extra steps.

194
00:14:01,433 --> 00:14:04,800
 so we thought we were finally done

195
00:14:04,800 --> 00:14:06,233
But then

196
00:14:06,233 --> 00:14:07,933
Apple said

197
00:14:08,433 --> 00:14:10,166
No.

198
00:14:10,166 --> 00:14:13,366
It was really upsetting

199
00:14:13,366 --> 00:14:14,766
 I don't have...

200
00:14:14,766 --> 00:14:19,333
I only have Mandarin screenshot, but I can read the message for you.

201
00:14:19,333 --> 00:14:22,000
 The In-App Purchase has been  rejected

202
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:26,266
For more information, refer to the App Review Notes

203
00:14:26,266 --> 00:14:31,033
All productIDs showed: “Developer action needed.”

204
00:14:31,033 --> 00:14:33,300
 So, what happened?

205
00:14:33,300 --> 00:14:36,200
Let’s refer to App Review Notes.

206
00:14:36,766 --> 00:14:38,400
There are too many words here. 

207
00:14:38,400 --> 00:14:41,500
We can only focus on the key words.

208
00:14:41,500 --> 00:14:43,633
 Apple rejected our submission

209
00:14:43,633 --> 00:14:46,766
because we introduced a new business model

210
00:14:46,766 --> 00:14:52,333
moving from subscriptions to including consumable products

211
00:14:52,433 --> 00:14:59,466
Apple wanted us to upload a new binary where FanKlub products are available to buy

212
00:14:59,466 --> 00:15:01,433
 But at that time,

213
00:15:01,433 --> 00:15:04,700
only the purchase flow was implemented

214
00:15:04,766 --> 00:15:08,466
All other FanKlub features were still in progress

215
00:15:08,466 --> 00:15:09,933
We wondered 

216
00:15:09,933 --> 00:15:15,300
Would unlocking a placeholder feature be enough to pass review?

217
00:15:15,300 --> 00:15:16,766
 To be safe,

218
00:15:16,766 --> 00:15:22,400
we waited and resubmitted after the full feature was ready.

219
00:15:22,400 --> 00:15:24,366
Before resubmission

220
00:15:24,366 --> 00:15:30,400
We confirm with our backend which APIs needed to go live in production

221
00:15:30,633 --> 00:15:36,166
We also enabled our billing system to handle the  sandbox transactions

222
00:15:36,166 --> 00:15:42,200
because initially, our production backend ignored sandbox transactions

223
00:15:42,633 --> 00:15:47,466
 We also recorded a demo video showing the full purchase flow

224
00:15:47,466 --> 00:15:49,433
 with detailed explanation

225
00:15:49,700 --> 00:15:53,933
And shared it with the App Review Notes

226
00:15:54,166 --> 00:15:57,766
 Finally, we renamed localized product name

227
00:15:57,766 --> 00:15:59,933
which I'll explain next.

228
00:16:01,833 --> 00:16:03,333
 At submission time,

229
00:16:03,333 --> 00:16:07,600
 we were blocked by the persistent productID error

230
00:16:07,600 --> 00:16:11,000
and we couldn't find any way to clear it.

231
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:12,766
 After several days,

232
00:16:12,766 --> 00:16:15,133
 we finally found a fix.

233
00:16:15,600 --> 00:16:16,766
 Just editing

234
00:16:16,766 --> 00:16:20,333
 the rejected products localized name

235
00:16:20,333 --> 00:16:22,766
 even just retype it,

236
00:16:22,766 --> 00:16:26,400
 reset the products and clear the error.

237
00:16:27,133 --> 00:16:28,333
 Finally, 

238
00:16:28,333 --> 00:16:30,266
 we resubmitted

239
00:16:30,266 --> 00:16:31,333
And

240
00:16:32,366 --> 00:16:35,066
we finally passed the review

241
00:16:35,566 --> 00:16:38,300
 Thank you.

242
00:16:38,766 --> 00:16:41,100
 But there's still a surprise.

243
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:42,766
 Surprisingly

244
00:16:42,766 --> 00:16:46,766
 Our backend showed no purchase activity.

245
00:16:49,366 --> 00:16:52,066
 how did Apple verify it?

246
00:16:52,066 --> 00:16:57,633
The demo video? Or were we just super lucky?

247
00:16:57,633 --> 00:16:59,466
 We'll never know.

248
00:16:59,466 --> 00:17:01,933
 But the lesson is  clear.

249
00:17:03,300 --> 00:17:05,300
 Submit early.

250
00:17:05,500 --> 00:17:09,766
 Apple review process can be full of surprises.

251
00:17:11,266 --> 00:17:12,500
 After sharing

252
00:17:12,500 --> 00:17:16,833
our implementation, there’s one more thing I want to stress.

253
00:17:16,833 --> 00:17:21,433
Before the United States allowed external checkout links this year

254
00:17:21,433 --> 00:17:25,866
 they are actually some regions already permitted external payments

255
00:17:25,866 --> 00:17:29,333
 like the European Union and Korea.

256
00:17:29,333 --> 00:17:30,766
 In Taiwan,

257
00:17:30,766 --> 00:17:36,533
In-App Purchase is still mandatory, but this global trend might eventually reach us

258
00:17:36,533 --> 00:17:39,500
 It's something we can keep an eye on.

259
00:17:41,300 --> 00:17:43,600
 To summarize the key takeaway

260
00:17:43,600 --> 00:17:49,400
here's a checklist for anyone who wishes to use a similar approach.

261
00:17:49,800 --> 00:17:54,700
First, coordinate with your backend about handling mixed receipts.

262
00:17:55,333 --> 00:17:58,766
Filter purchases by productID.

263
00:17:58,766 --> 00:18:02,933
 Test both flows using the tools we covered earlier.

264
00:18:03,800 --> 00:18:07,266
 Leave buffer time  for app review process.

265
00:18:08,433 --> 00:18:09,566
 And

266
00:18:09,566 --> 00:18:15,600
 ensure your product  is available to purchase during the app review process.

267
00:18:15,866 --> 00:18:18,400
The hybrid approach isn’t perfect

268
00:18:18,500 --> 00:18:20,233
it adds complexity

269
00:18:20,466 --> 00:18:26,166
but it gave us a low risk way to adopt StoreKit 2 for our new feature

270
00:18:28,466 --> 00:18:31,000
The issues we faced were small,

271
00:18:31,100 --> 00:18:34,133
 but difficult to find solutions on the internet.

272
00:18:34,300 --> 00:18:37,300
I hope this session saves you time

273
00:18:38,033 --> 00:18:41,433
Before we wrap up, I want to introduce FanKlub

274
00:18:41,433 --> 00:18:45,566
 a brand new feature in the KKBOX app.

275
00:18:45,566 --> 00:18:51,333
 FanKlub helps fans feel a deeper intimacy with their idols

276
00:18:52,333 --> 00:18:54,766
